@node "Support" "Support"
@next "Installing"
@prev "License"
@{u}SUPPORT@{uu}

If you find any problems/bugs with Cyclone you can obtain advice and support
from the author by sending a NetMail to 2:250/366.12 with the subject line
CYCLONE-SUPPORT. You can also send e-mail to gary@empire.abel.co.uk .Please
use that subject line or your message will end up mixed in with my normal
mail and may take a while to process.

Please Note: My old 2:259/2.23 address is no longer valid for support mail.

The official Cyclone web site is at http://www.abel.co.uk/~empire/

If you have access to the Z2-R25 Fidonet backbone you can also fix into
the CYCLONE echo. Bug fixes and new revisions of the program will always
be announced here first, and the files themselves can be obtained via the
file echo CYCLONE_FILE, which is available from 2:250/366 and 2:250/194.



IMPORTANT NOTE
--------------

Please include as much information as you can when reporting a bug
or problem. Details that you think are insignificant may well be the key
to getting things fixed. In particular, please include the version numbers
of Cyclone, FastImport, MUI and AmigaOS. Details about your hardware are
essential as well.

Anyone who mails me saying 'Xyz function isn't working! Why?' without
giving any more details may not like the reply they get back... This
goes double if the answer to your question can be found in this file.

@endnode

@node "Installing" "Installing"
@next "GetStarted"
@prev "Support"
@{u}Installing Cyclone@{uu}


Before installing Cyclone make sure your C: directory contains a copy of the
Amiga Technologies Installer program. Double click on the 'Install' icon and
the standard installer program will load. Just follow the on-screen prompts.

When installation is complete you MUST re-boot your Amiga before trying to run
Cyclone or lots of unspecified Nasty Things will happen to your system.

The first thing that appears after you load Cyclone will be a name requester,
just type in your name here. It must be your real name, not a nick name or
alias as many networks, Fidonet included, do not allow false names.

Next up is the address requester. Here you need to type in the network address
given to you by the Sysop of the Bulletin Board System you are pointing from.
Don't worry if you have been given addresses for more than one network, just
enter your Fidonet address here. The others can be configured later.

If you are using an unregistered copy of Cyclone a requester reminding you to
pay your @{"registration" link "reg" 0} fee will pop up here. It will appear every time you load
Cyclone without a keyfile present. You can click it away after a few moments.

Once that's out of the way the Area list will pop up. At the moment you will
only have one area available. This is the Netmail, or private mail, area for
the address you entered a few moments ago. When you set up other network
addresses Netmail areas will be created for them also.

@endnode

@node "GetStarted" "Getting Started"
@next "Menus"
@prev "Installing"
@{u}Getting Started@{uu}


Cyclone's main screen consists of the header text area, main message display
and an icon bank. The first two are pretty self-explanatory, but the icons may
need explaining :


@{b}Write new message@{ub}

Loads your configured text editor and lets you enter a new message. When
loaded the text editor will display a skeleton message consisting of the
write-header and signature strings you have defined for the current area.
Cyclone is frozen while you enter the message.

Before the text editor loads you will be presented with a message header
window. Here you can enter the name and network address of the intended
recipient, as well as the message subject line.

When you have finished editing the mssage, save and quit the text editor. Your
message will be saved to the current are with an E or Export flag.


@{b}Reply to current message@{ub}

Similar to the Write function, except that you will be presented with the full
text of the current message included between your intro and sig strings. Each
line of the message will be prefixed with the initials of the sender and a
quote (>) mark.


@{b}Delete message@{ub}

Removes the current message. There is no way back once you have deleted a
message -- It's gone for good.


@{b}Back in thread@{ub}

Jumps back to the last message with the same subject line as the one you are
currently on.


@{b}Move back@{ub}

Moves to the previous message.


@{b}Move forward@{ub}

Moves to the next message.


@{b}Forward in thread@{ub}

Jumps to the next message with the same subject line as the one you are on.


@{b}Edit message@{ub}

Loads the text editor so you can change the contents of the current message.
Pops up the header window so you can change the details there too.


@{b}Message list@{ub}

Displays a list of to/from/subj/date data for all messages in the current
area. Clicking on a message displays it in full. The first four buttons below
the list enable you to set/unset the Export and Marked flags.


@{b}Area List@{ub}

Displays a list of all available message areas. Clicking on an area saves all
data for the current area and loads in the new one.
@endnode

