@{u}Misc Utilities@{uu}

Cyclone includes several small utilities. Most of them are a little kludgy
so please read the documentation carefuly.


 @{"Punarc        " link "Punarc" 0}  The universal unarchiver
 @{"Maketags      " link "Maketags" 0}  Create your own taglines

@endnode

@node "Punarc" "Punarc"
@next "maketags"
@prev "Utils"
@{b}Punarc 0.2a@{ub}


Punarc is an amazing little util by Stephen Brookes. It checks the format
of an compressed file and calls the correct archive command. If you wish
to use Cyclone with more than one type of incoming compressed mail (Lha,
Lzx or Zip), then you will need to use Punarc.

Simply install Punarc as described in the docs below, and replace the
Prefs/General/Expand string with 'C:Punarc' (without the quotes).


-[Original Punarc Docs]---------------------------------------------------


Punarc remains (C) Stephen Brookes, but may be freely distributed.

I accept no responsibility for any unwelcome effects resulting from the use of
any information or software in this archive, it's all your own fault.



This hardly needs a doc. Errr, maybe it does, but I hate docs so this is short
and messy :)

This was mostly written to fix many troubles I've had with fido tossers, it is
also used by another (unreleased (forever :) ) programme of mine, and to save
me trying to remember all the commands for every wierd archiver.

In all these cases it functions as a CLI based unarchiver that tries to
present a uniform interface between user and archive. With a different config
file it could process files in other ways, but that's just confusing matters
more than they are allready :)

This is only the second version, so it may have some bugs. Please report any
troubles.

V39+ is (probably) required!



In this archive, you should find...

'Punarc' goes in 'C:' 'Punarc.cfg' goes in 'S:' 'Punarc.doc' goes in the bin.


In use, you just replace the usual 'lha x <file>' or whatever for whatever
type of archive, with 'punarc <file>'. For just about any archive, this will
unarc to the current directory. To unarc to a different destination 'punarc
<file> <dest dir>' will generally work, even with the likes of 'UNZIP'.

Of course, you have to actually have the correct archiver available, it's
probably best to remove any entries in the config for archivers you don't
have.

Setting up the cfg file is a little tricky, but it is mostly explained in the
file. Chances are, you won't have to touch it anyway, except to remove entries
for arhivers you don't have.



Stephen Brookes 2:259/2.15
@endnode

@node "Maketags" "Maketags"
@next "Reg"
@prev "Punarc"
@{b}Maketags@{ub}

Maketags converts an ASCII tagline file into the .DAT tag files used
by Cyclone. See the included ASCII tag files for the format used.

@endnode

