@node "Project_menu" "Project Menu"
@{u}Project Menu@{uu}


@{b}Import Packet@{ub}

Loads the FastImport program, which will unpack and convert any valid Fidonet
type mail packets found the in the INBOUND directory. After the import
operation is completed Cyclone will perform a re-index and validation pass
over the entire message base.


@{b}Export Packet@{ub}

Scans the message base for any messages marked with an E (Export) flag and
bundles them into Fidonet type packets, to be placed in the OUTBOUND
directory.


@{b}Purge@{ub}

Performs a purge operation on the current message area. Any scrap or unused
data will be removed from the message base. If the area contains more messages
than specified using the purge limit slider (see Preferences/Areas) then
excess messages will be deleted.

WARNING! Check that the area's purge limit slider is at a sensible value
before performing a purge operation. It's very easy to wipe out a whole area
by not checking this.


@{b}Purge All@{ub}

Performs purge operationon all areas. This function may take some time to
complete on verylarge message bases.


@{b}Poll@{ub}

Loads your specified mailer program (Trapdoor, GMS etc.) and attempts to dial
your boss node. The poll command string is taken from the network associated
with the current area (see Preferences/Networks).


@{b}About MUI@{ub}

Gives some information on the MUI system.


@{b}About Cyclone@{ub}

Gives some information on Cyclone. If you are a registered user your serial
number will be displayed in this window.


@{b}Quit@{ub}

I don't need to explain this, do I?  I hope not...  ;-)
@endnode

@node "Message_Menu" "Message Menu"
@next "Misc_Menu"
@prev "Project_menu"
@{u}Message Menu@{uu}

@{b}Write@{ub}

Loads your configured text editor and lets you enter a new message. When
loaded the text editor will display a skeleton message consisting of the
write-header and signature strings you have defined for the current area.
Cyclone is frozen while you enter the message.

Before the text editor loads you will be presented with a message header
window. Here you can enter the name and network address of the intended
recipient, as well as the message subject line.

When you have finished editing the mssage, save and quit the text editor. Your
message will be saved to the current are with an E or Export flag.


@{b}Reply@{ub}

Similar to the Write function, except that you will be presented with the full
text of the current message included between your intro and sig strings. Each
line of the message will be prefixed with the initials of the sender and a
quote (>) mark.


@{b}Cross Reply@{ub}

Similar to the standard Reply function, except you will be asked for a new
area into which your reply will be posted.


@{b}Forward@{ub}

Copies the current message into a new area adding a short header showing the
original date and poster of the message.


@{b}Edit@{ub}

Loads the text editor so you can change the contents of the current message.
Pops up the header window so you can change the details there too.


@{b}Crash Deliver@{ub}

Exports the current message as crash mail. Only the current message is
exported, but you can export messages later and they will be added to the
original crash mail packet.


@{b}Edit Header@{ub}

Pops up the header box for the current message, allowing you to change most
details. Currently the e-mail address cannot be changed using the Edit Header
function. Use the full edit option for that.


@{b}Mark@{ub}

Gives the current message an M (Marked) flag.


@{b}Delete@{ub}

Deletes the current message.


@{b}Save as ASCII@{ub}

Dumps the current message into a standard text file. All kludges will be
stripped, but Seen-By lines are not.


@{b}Send to Clipboard@{ub}

Copies the current message to the system clipboard.


@{b}Catch Up@{ub}

Removes U (Unread) flags from all messages in the current area.


@{b}View AmigaGuide@{ub}

Loads Multiview to display AmigaGuide codes embedded in the current message.
Also works with other text-code datatypes such as HTDS.


@{b}View FTX@{ub}

Loads the VFTX module to interpret any FTX Level 1 codes present in the
current message. See VFTX documentation for more details.
@endnode

@node "Misc_Menu" "Misc Menu"
@next "Windows_Menu"
@prev "Message_Menu"
@{u}Misc Menu@{uu}


@{b}View HTML@{ub}

Loads the MoreHTML utility to display HTML messages. MoreHTML must be present
in your C: directory.


@{b}Area Search@{ub}

From this window you can search the current area for a specified word(s). The
check boxes in the middle of the window control what fields should be searched
for the keywords. If you select the 'Marked' box then the keywords you have
entered are ignored and Cyclone will search for any messages with a (M) Marked
flag.


@{b}Add Sender to UserList@{ub}

Creates an entry in the User List containing the name and address for the
sender of the current message.


@{b}Add Sender to NukeList@{ub}

Creates an entry in the Nuke List containing the name of the sender of the
current message. Any incoming messages from this person will now be deleted at
import time.


@{b}Add Subject to NukeList@{ub}

Creates an entry in the Nuke List containing the subject line of the current
message. Any incoming messages containing this subject line will be deleted at
import time.


@{b}View UserList@{ub}

Pops open the User List window :

To enter a new name in the User List just click the 'Add' button and fill in
the three required fields. Clicking 'Del' will delete the selected entry.


@{b}View NukeList@{ub}

Pops open the Nuke List window :

To enter a new keyword in the Nuke List just click 'Add' and enter the
required keyword into the string gadget at the bottom of the window. The four
check boxes above it control what fields should be scanned for the keyword.

Any inbound message will that keyword present in the selected fields will be
deleted at import time.
@endnode

@node "Windows_Menu" "Windows Menu"
@next "Movement_Menu"
@prev "Misc_Menu"
@{u}Windows Menu@{uu}


@{b}Area List@{ub}

Opens the Area List window.


@{b}Message List@{ub}

Opens the Message List window.


@{b}File Request@{ub}

The file request (Freq) window allows you to request files from any Fidonet
node that supports this feature.

To request a file just type the address of the fido node into the string
gadget at the top of the window. Then enter the files you want in the string
gadget in the bottom part of the window.

When you close the window a Freq (.REQ) packet will be created in the OUTBOUND
directory. The next time you poll the requested node the request packet will
be sent and, if you're lucky, the files will be downloaded.

When you type in a fido address any .REQ files destined for that address will
be loaded into the Freq list for editing. Cyclone can load REQ files created
by any Amiga mail package.


@{b}Fast Search List@{ub}

Displays a window containing a list of all messages in the current area that
have a TO: field matching the string you enter here. Defaults to 'ALL'.
Clicking on an entry takes you to that message.


@{b}Thread List@{ub}

Displays a window containing a list of all messages the have the same subject
line as the one you are currently on. Clicking on an entry takes you to that
message.
@endnode

@node "Movement_Menu" "Movement Menu"
@next "Prefs_Menu"
@prev "Windows_Menu"
@{u}Movement Menu@{uu}


@{b}First Message@{ub}

Jumps to message #1 in the current area.


@{b}Last Message@{ub}

Jumps to the highest message in the current area.

@{b}
Next Unread@{ub}

Moves to the next message marked with a U (Unread) flag.


@{b}Next Marked@{ub}

Moves to the next message marked with a M (Marked) flag.


@{b}Next Export@{ub}

Moves to the next message marked with a E (Export) flag.


@{b}Next Personal@{ub}

Moves to the next message that is addressed to you.


@{b}Prev Unread@{ub}

Moves backwards to the last message marked with a U (Unread) flag.


@{b}Prev Marked@{ub}

Moves backwards to the last message marked with a M (Marked) flag.


@{b}Prev Export@{ub}

Moves backwards the last message marked with a E (Export) flag.


@{b}Prev Personal@{ub}

Moves backward to the last message that is addressed to you.

@endnode

@node "Prefs_Menu" "Preferences Menu"
@prev "Movement_Menu"
@{u}Preferences Menu@{uu}


@{b}Tosser@{ub}

This window provides control over the mail tosser/parser.

 Name          : The name you are known by.

 User Alias    : Your alias. Used in any areas with the 'Alias' flag set.
                 Please note that aliases are prohibited on some networks.

 Dupe Checking : Toggles duplicate message checking. If you rarely get dupes
                 it's best to leave this disabled as dupe checking can slow
                 import operations considerably, especially using larger
                 table sizes.

                 NOTE: If you are using the AmiGate utility with Cyclone
                 you *must* disable the dupe checker otherwise it will
                 reject unique messages. (This is a bug in AmiGate not
                 Cyclone).

 Table Size    : Size of the table used to store message IDs. The entire
                 table must be scanned for every message imported, so keep
                 it as small as possible.

@{b}General@{ub}

This window shows all the paths and command strings used by Cyclone. Some of
them, such as the editor & poll commands, must be altered to fit your system.

 Editor     : Path and filename of the text editor used for entering and
              editing messages.
 Edit File  : Temporary file used to store the message being edited.
 Inbound    : Path of the directory where incoming packets are stored
 Outbound   : Path of the directory where outgoing packets are sotred
 Compress   : Master Compress command. Name and path of the archiver used
              to compress outgoing mail. This command is used only as the
              default for new networks.
 Expand     : Name and path of the archiver used to uncompress inbound mail
 Poll       : Master Poll command. Name and path of the mailer used to send
              and receive mail. This command is used only as the default for
              new networks.
 Pkt Backup : Path of the directory used to backup incoming mail packets
              before an import operation. Entering a null path disables
              packet backup.
 Ascii Save : Default path for saved messages.
 F-Attach   : Default path for file attaches
 Arexx      : Default path for Arexx Scripts. Best left as Cyclone:Arexx
 File Backup: Path of the directory used to backup any files in the INBOUND
              directory before an import operation. Entering a null path
              disables file backup.
 Polling    : Controls the method used to call the mailer program.

@{b}Areas@{ub}

Attributes for all available areas can be changed from this window. Areas are
listed on the left hand side, with flags at the top right and strings below
them.

The Flags are:

 Netmail  : Sets this area to a Netmail area.
 Frozen   : Prevents Purge operations.
 Read Only: Prevents message delete.
 R. Tags  : Appends a random tagline to any message you write.
 E-Mail   : Flags a netmail area as connected to an e-mail gateway.
 Alias    : Use alias instead of real user name.

See below of explanations of the Hdr, Sig and Origin lines.


@{b}Name@{ub}

If you dislike the tag name of an area you can enter a replacement name
here. This will be used by the area list window only. Entering a ! as
the first character of the name causes it to appear highlighted. The *
does the same, but for bold text.

The '_' and '-' characters will cause a horizonal bar to be drawn below or
above the name of the area in the area list.

@{b}Networks@{ub}

Any additional FTNs you wish to access are configured from this window. Please
note that new areas will use the first listed network. If areas are to use
data for other nets they must be attached to that network manually via the
Preferences/Areas window.

Netmail areas for new networks will be automaticaly created when you close
the Networks window.


@{b}GUI@{ub}

Here you can control what, if any, entries on the message and area lists
should be picked out in bold or white text. Two options that may need an
explanation are:

 End Area Popup    : Opens the area list window when you press the right
                     arrow keyon the last message in the area.

 Two Pass Quoting  : Enables the new two-pass quote parser. This may
                     result in more sensible interpretation of quotes
                     when replying to messages.

@{b}Message Display@{ub}

Format Codes
-----------

   Invalid Leading : Text style codes will be ignored if any of the chars
                     in this string are present in front of the code.

   Whitespace      : Characters entered here are considered to be white
                     space.

   Terminators     : Text style codes will be ignored if any of the chars
                     in this string are present behind the code.


Distances
---------

   Attributes      : The maximum number of chars a text style code may
                     affect.

   Quotes          : The number of chars at the beginning of a line that
                     will be scanned for quote (>) chars.


Colours
-------

  This page contains four colour buttons that are used to specify the
  colours used for different quote levels.


Misc
----

  Sig Seperator    : Replaces any occurence of '-- ' with a solid
                     horizontal line.

  Hide PGP Keys    : Hides PGP keys and replaces them with a 'PGP Key
                     detected' string. [Not currently available - GC]

  Text Styles      : Toggles recognition of text syles.

  Hide UU-enocodes : Hides uu-encodes and replaces them with a 'UUencode
                     detected' string.

  Parse FTX codes  : Toggles recognition of FTX colour codes.


@{b}Arexx@{ub}

This is where you can enter details of ARexx scripts to be listed in the
ARexx menu. Three parametes are taken for every script:

 Name   : The name that will appear on the ARexx menu
 Script : Path to the actual script file
 Output : Text output from the script is sent here.
          Best left as NIL: or CON:

The ARexx interpreter (RexxMast) must be running before any ARexx scripts
can be called.


@{b}Mail Shunting@{ub}

Mail shunting is one of Cyclone's most powerful features. It takes inbound
messages and re-directs them to a new area based on keywords present in the
subject line. Each 'Shunt Link' requires three parameters:

 From Area   : Area to be scanned for matching messages
 To Area     : Shunted messages end up here
 Subject     : Messages with this subject are shunted

You can place a 4D fido address in the Subject field here and any messaged
originating from that address will be shunted.


@{b}MUI@{ub}

Calls up the Magic User Interface preferences and configuration program.

@{b}
Write Intros@{ub}

This window is used to create headers for any messages you create using the
'Write' function. To create a new header just click the 'Add' button. Several
control codes are available in Write Headers:

 |n   Newline
 |t   Name of intended recipient
 |T   As above but first name only
 |d   Current date
 |u   Your name

The normal * (bold), _ (Underline) and / (Italic) codes can be used here as
well. A preview of how your header will look appears at the bottom of the
window.

If you find the built-in editor limiting all Write Intro headers are stored as
plain ASCII in the file 'Cyclone:Wintros.Dat'. Be careful not to let your
headers exceed 350 characters if editing this file with a text editor.

If you wish an area to use a new header you must configure the area via the
Preferences/Areas window.


@{b}Reply Intros@{ub}

As above except headers created here will be used when you reply to a message.
Additional codes available :

 |f Name of sender.
 |F As above but first name only

ASCII data for reply headers is stored in 'Cyclone:Rintros.Dat'. The 350
char limit applies here also.


@{b}Signatures@{ub}

Signatures are small texts appended to the bottom of any non-netmail messages
you write. ASCII data for the signatures is held in the file
'Cyclone:Sigs.Dat'. Sigs can be quite elaborate, but it's best not to use the
/*_ control chars because all fido message editing software will interpret
these in slightly different ways. What looks good using Cyclone may look silly
using other software.


@{b}Origins@{ub}

Origin lines are placed below a signature line and prefixed with ' * Origin'.
They are supposed to carry the name of the node at which the message
originated, but many people use them as mini taglines. The /*_ control chars
are available for origins, but | prefixed codes are not. ASCII data for
origins is stored in 'Cyclone:Origins.Dat' with a 58 char line limit.


@{b}Hide Kludges@{ub}

This option toggles whether Cyclone will show internal FTN control, or
'kludge', codes when displaying messages.


@{b}Hide Seen-Bys.@{ub}

As above, but applies to Seen-By kludges. Every FTN node a message passes
through adds it's address to the seen-by lines. Can be useful for tracing the
route a message has taken over the network.
@endnode


@{b}Highlight Kludges@{ub}

When selected this causes kludges to be shown in white. Has no effect if the
Hide Kludges option in checked.

@node "Arexx_Menu" "Arexx Menu"
@next "Misc_Tech"
@prev "Prefs_Menu"
@{u}Arexx Menu@{uu}

Any Arexx scripts entered into the Prefs/Arexx window are listed here.

NOTE: The Arexx menu is only updated when Cyclone first loads.

@endnode


@node "Misc_Tech" "Rambles"
@next "soapbox"
@prev "ARexx_Menu"

@{u}Technical Rambles@{uu}

Welcome!

This is the bit of the guide where I get to throw a few useless statistics
at you.


For those who are interested, Cyclone was written on the following Amiga
system:
            Commodore Amiga A1200 Rev 1A
            Apollo 1240 Accelerator (68040@33MHz)
            16Mb 60ns Fast Ram
            Seagate ST51270AV 1.27Gb IDE Hard Drive
            GoldStar GCD-R540B Atapi CD-Rom Drive
            NEC MultiSync II Monitor
            Genuine Microsoft Mouse!  ;-)

And the software used:

            Amiga-E V3.1i
            GoldED v3.1.4
            PhxAss v4.34
            IRA v1.02

@endnode


@node "soapbox" "The Soapbox"
@next "thanks"
@prev "Misc_Tech"

@{b}@{u}The Soapbox@{ub}@{uu}

Nobody expects to get rich writing Amiga shareware. Mostly we do it because
we like developing software and providing people with something that lets
them get a little more out of their computer. However large and complex
projects, of which Cyclone is just one example, take years to develop
and consume large amounts of time and money.

Shareware offers an acceptable solution. The user gets good software at
bargain prices, and the programmer receives some compensation for his
work. Everybody is happy.

When this works it's great, but increasingly it isn't working in quite such
a rosy fasion. Large numbers of people make daily use of programs but refuse
to pay the small registration fee, even after the evaluation period is over.
That's bad, but what is much worse are the users who simply jump to another
program when the evaluation period runs out.

Shareware is the Amiga's most valuable resource. With commercial software
development drying up it's changed from being a nice backup to the engine
that keeps the Amiga world turning. Without support from users that engine
will falter and fail.

Programmers are just like anybody else. If they pour all their resources
into a project and then see it ignored or abused they will pack up and
go do something else.

To those who abuse shareware I say this: Next time you load your favourite
shareware program, consider paying the few pounds, dollars or marks the
author requests. It buys you a lot -- an enhanced program, the gratitude
of the programmer and the knowledge that you've done a bit to help save
the Amiga's last lifeline.

Finaly, I'd like to extend my thanks, not only to those who have registered
Cyclone, but to anyone who regularly registers shareware. You can sleep
easy knowing you're one of the good guys.


@{b}@{u}Off the Soapbox@{ub}@{uu}

By now you probably think I'm on the verge bailing out, but I'm not. My
commitment to Cyclone, and to the Amiga, remains undimmed. As long as I
think people appreciate my work I'll be here battering away at the
keyboard.

If the ship sinks I'll be the last one into the life raft...

@endnode

@node "Thanks" "Greetings and Thanks"
@prev "SoapBox"

I'd like to thank the following people :


 Matthew Kichenside   ; For the Icons.

 Anthony Brice        ; For his invaluable help in getting the e-mail
                        parts of Cyclone running.


 ...and all those good souls who have parted with hard earned cash to
 register Cyclone.


@endnode
